 The two JSON files play different roles, similar to infra:

myapp-overview.json

    - A general service overview dashboard.

    - Use it to show high‑level metrics: request rate, error rate, p95 latency, pod restarts, deployment status, etc.

    - This is what most people (devs, QA, product) will open first when they “just want to see if myapp is healthy.”

myapp-slo.json

    - A focused SLO / error‑budget dashboard.

    - Dedicated to SLO metrics and burn‑rate series you just implemented:

        SLO target (99.9%).

        Error budget remaining.

        Burn‑rate over 5m/30m windows.

        Historical SLO performance.

    - This is mainly for SRE/on‑call and people who care about reliability across weeks/months, not just “is it red right now.”

Reason to split:

    - The overview dashboard stays simple and operational (“is myapp ok now?”).

    - The SLO dashboard can be more analytical and long‑term (“are we on track to meet our SLO?”), without cluttering the main view.